# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: architecture-of-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:architecture-of-scotland/40-george-square] The tower was originally named after the Scottish Enlightenment philosopher David Hume, who was an alumnus of the university.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/40-george-square] In September 2020, in response to the Black Lives Matter movement, the university announced that they would be renaming the tower to 40 George Square.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/40-george-square] The tower was built as part of a significant 1960s redevelopment of George Square by the university, which saw the demolition of numerous Georgian terraced houses and tenements to make way for new university buildings.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/40-george-square] The redevelopments were opposed by community groups and organisations, such as the Cockburn Association and the Scottish Georgian Society.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/40-george-square] Other buildings constructed included the university's Main Library and Appleton Tower.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/40-george-square] The building was designed for the university's Arts Faculty by the Scottish modernist architect Robert Matthew of Robert Matthew Johnson-Marshall & Partners (RMJM), alongside the structural engineering firm Blyth & Blyth.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/40-george-square] The tower is 43 metres (141 ft), and 14 storeys high.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/40-george-square] To the rear of the tower there is a row of lecture theatres, which are joined to the tower via a lower ground floor.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/40-george-square] The lower ground floor, known as the Hub, includes a café and shop surrounding a central atrium.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/40-george-square] The structure of the tower is made from reinforced concrete with brick infill, and is clad with slabs of polished black slate and York sandstone.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/40-george-square] The block of lecture theatres is similarly made of reinforced concrete and clad in York sandstone.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/40-george-square] The construction took place from 1960 until 1963, and was carried out by the contractor firm Crudens.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/40-george-square] In 2014, the lower ground floor was renovated to create the DHT Hub, including teaching space, a café and a EUSA shop.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/40-george-square] The renovations cost £15 million and won the RICS Conservation Award, Scottish Design Awards commendation, and a GIA Awards commendation.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] The nucleus of the estate was a farm of 100 acres (0.40 km2), called Cartleyhole, nicknamed Clarty (i.e., muddy) Hole, and was bought by Scott on the lapse of his lease (1811) of the neighbouring house of Ashestiel.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] Scott renamed it "Abbotsford" after a neighbouring ford used by the monks of Melrose Abbey.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] Following a modest enlargement of the original farmhouse in 1811–1812, massive expansions took place in 1816–1819 and 1822–1824.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] In this mansion Scott gathered a large library, a collection of ancient furniture, arms and armour, and other relics and curiosities especially connected with Scottish history, notably the Celtic Torrs Pony-cap and Horns and the Woodwrae Stone, all now in the Museum of Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] Scott described the resulting building as "a sort of romance in Architecture" and "a kind of Conundrum Castle to be sure".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] The last and principal acquisition was that of Toftfield (afterwards named Huntlyburn), purchased in 1817.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] The new house was then begun and completed in 1824.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] The general ground-plan is a parallelogram, with irregular outlines, one side overlooking the Tweed; and the style is mainly the Scottish Baronial.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] With his architects William Atkinson and Edward Blore Scott was a pioneer of the Scottish Baronial style of architecture: the house is recognized as a highly influential creation with themes from Abbotsford being reflected across many buildings in the Scottish Borders and beyond.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] The manor as a whole appears as a "castle-in-miniature", with small towers and imitation battlements decorating the house and garden walls.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] Into various parts of the fabric were built relics and curiosities from historical structures, such as the doorway of the old Tolbooth in Edinburgh.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] Scott collected many of these curiosities to be built into the walls of the South Garden, which previously hosted a colonnade of gothic arches along the garden walls.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] Along the path of the former colonnade sits the remains of Edinburgh's 15th century Mercat Cross and several examples of classical sculpture.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] The estate and its neo-Medieval features nod towards Scott's desire for a historical feel, but the writer ensured that the house would provide all the comforts of modern living.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] As a result, Scott used the space as a proving-ground for new technologies.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] The house was outfitted with early gas lighting and pneumatic bells connecting residents with servants elsewhere in the house.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] Scott had only enjoyed his residence one year when (1825) he met with that reverse of fortune which involved the estate in debt.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] In 1830, the library and museum were presented to him as a free gift by the creditors.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] The property was wholly disencumbered in 1847 by Robert Cadell, the publisher, who cancelled the bond upon it in exchange for the family's share in the copyright of Sir Walter's works.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] Scott's only son Walter did not live to enjoy the property, having died on his way from India in 1847.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] Among subsequent possessors were Scott's grandson Walter Scott Lockhart (later Walter Lockhart Scott, 1826–1853), his younger sister Charlotte Harriet Jane Hope-Scott (née Lockhart) 1828–1858, J.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] Hope Scott, QC, and his daughter (Scott's great-granddaughter), the Hon.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] The house was opened to the public in 1833, but continued to be occupied by Scott's descendants until 2004.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] The last of his direct descendants to hold the Lairdship of Abbotsford was his great-great-great-granddaughter Dame Jean Maxwell-Scott (8 June 1923 – 5 May 2004).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] She inherited it from her elder sister Patricia Maxwell-Scott in 1998.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] The sisters turned the house into one of Scotland's premier tourist attractions, after they had to rely on paying visitors to afford the upkeep of the house.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] It had electricity installed only in 1962.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] On Dame Jean's death the Abbotsford Trust was established to safeguard the estate.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] In 2005, Scottish Borders Council considered an application by a property developer to build a housing estate on the opposite bank of the River Tweed from Abbotsford, to which Historic Scotland and the National Trust for Scotland objected.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] There have been modifications to the proposed development, but it is still being opposed in 2020.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] Sir Walter Scott rescued the "jougs" from Threave Castle in Dumfries and Galloway and attached them to the castellated gateway he built at Abbotsford.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] Tweedbank railway station is located near to Abbotsford.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] Abbotsford gave its name to the Abbotsford Club, founded by William Barclay Turnbull in 1833 or 1834 in Scott's honour, and a successor to the Bannatyne and Maitland Clubs.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] It was a text publication society, which existed to print and publish historical works connected with Scott's writings.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] Its publications extended from 1835 to 1864.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] In August 2012, a new Visitor Centre opened at Abbotsford which houses a small exhibition, gift shop and Ochiltree's café with views over the house and grounds.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] The house re-opened to the public after extensive renovations in July 2013.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/abbotsford-house] In 2014 it won the European Union Prize for Cultural Heritage / Europa Nostra Award for its then recent conservation project.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/act-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] The Scottish origin of Menelaws was confirmed by the architect himself to A.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Granville, an English traveler who published a report of his journey in London in 1828.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] There is no other reliable evidence of his early years, education and experience prior to arriving in Russia in 1784.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Members of Menelaws family were construction contractors in Argyll; Howard Colvin and Dmitry Shvidkovsky suggest that Adam Menelaws belonged to the same family, but this opinion has not been reliably confirmed by archive research.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Historians split over the year of his birth: a 1784 immigration record suggests that he arrived in Russia at the age of 35, i.e. born in or around 1748, while the funeral records of the English church in Saint Petersburg state the year of his birth as 1756.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] In 1803 Menelaws asserted that he hails from a noble English family, but Russian authorities refused to honour his claim.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] In early 1780s Charles Cameron, an architect employed by Catherine II since 1779, published a job offer in *Edinburgh Evening News*, signed *Catherine of Russia*, inviting skilled construction workers to join his Tsarskoye Selo project.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] 73 craftsmen, including Adam Menelaws, agreed to move to Russia (many took their families with them), causing a futile protest of the Foreign Office.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] All were sufficiently qualified to become professional architects or at least architect's trainees in Russia; Cameron ranked Menelaws as the one of two best stonemasons – the "vaulting master".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Menelaws signed for a three-year contract to build the Cold Baths near Saint Petersburg, agreeing also to train a class of Russian craftsmen.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Apparently the number of Scottish professionals was too big for Cameron, and one year later Menelaws left him and joined the service of Nikolay Lvov.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Lvov, an amateur composer, poet and Palladian architect was at that time aide to statesman Alexander Bezborodko.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Historians divide over his role in Menelaws career: tradition held it that Lvov promoted Menelaws, introducing him to the Crown projects, while later researchers assert that, on the contrary, Lvov's influence slowed down Menelaws career.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Instead of architecture, in May 1785 Lvov engaged Menelaws and William Heste in search for coal fossils (at that time Russian metallurgy was dependent on either charcoal or imports from England and Wales).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] In 1786 Menelaws found commercial-grade ("not inferior to that of Newcastle") coal near Borovichi; by 1790 the coal research team increased to 10 professionals.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] It is quite likely, however, that Lvov used the state-sponsored quest for coal as a cover to extract a talented architect for his own use: in 1785–1794 Menelaws was regularly involved in Lvov's construction projects.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Another Scot, Walter Irving, was employed by Lvov to construct his idealist *Sun Temple*, a country estate in Tver Oblast; its circular arcade, resembling the henges of Britain, was later recreated in Menelaws' own designs.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] The rotunda motive, common to Menelaws later works, was most likely inspired by Lvov.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Menelaws married Elizabeth Cave in 1792; the ceremony was attended by Lvov, Alexey Olenin (president of the Imperial Academy of Arts) and numerous members of the English and Scottish diaspora.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] In 1795 Menelaws began gradually separating from Lvov's service after the construction of the Saint Joseph cathedral in Mahilyow, but the two remained in contact until Lvov's sudden death in 1803.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Meanwhile, Menelaws remained a Russian state servant of a small rank since his arrival.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] After Lvov's death he attempted to retire immediately, but, faced with refusal in pension benefits, preferred to remain in service until 1806.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] According to Anthony Cross, "the late burgeoning of Menelaws talent" probably occurred only after Lvov' death, during his work for the Razumovsky family.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] In the 19th century Menelaws created a string of English gardens for the Razumovskys; the best known, in Gorenki (present-day Balashikha), was included in John Claudius Loudon's *An Encyclopedia of Gardening* for its landscaping and a private botanical garden.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Historians split on the issue whether Gorenki was designed primarily by Menelaws or by Lvov.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] In 1801–1802 Menelaws designed and built the Razumovsky Palace in Basmanny District of Moscow; the palace was destroyed by the Fire of 1812 and later reconstructed by Afanasy Grigoriev.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Another large park, Stroganov's Maryino Estate, was laid down near Saint Peterburg in 1813.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] All these landscaping projects perished by the end of 19th century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Menelaws park designs always employed a Gothic ruin as a visual anchor.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Menelaws was instrumental in operations of the Maryino school established by the Golitsyns in 1819, teaching the peasants the craft of cob construction.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Introduction of cob technology in Russia is usually credited to Lvov, but may also be linked directly to Menelaws's Scottish experience.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Dmitry Shvidkovsky suggested that Menelaws, not Cameron, was the designer of the Razumovsky palace in Baturin, but other historians reject this opinion.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] In the 1810s Alexander I invited Menelaws to redesign the Alexander's Park in Tsarskoye Selo, starting with an old dilapidated menagerie.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] The new plan proposed by Menelaws created an illusion of a completely novel design, yet carefully preserved the structure of a regular park shaped in the previous century; according to Lvov, Menelaws "merged the art of Kent and Le Nôtre".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Use of an eclectic, pan-European romanticism was justified as a symbol of the New Europe shaped at the Congress of Vienna, but was also a sign of Alexander's turn to mysticism.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Alexander's Park was occupied by Nicholas I, then heir presumptive, who also leaned to eclecticism and medieval legacy, as would be evidenced later by his reign.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Nicholas became Menelaws' "most appreciative patron who provided him with the opportunity at a very advanced stage of life".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Indeed, his most important commission, the Alexandria Park, was started when the architect was at least around 70 years old.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Shortly before his death in 1824, Alexander I granted a 285-acre (1.15 km2) lot of land on the coast of Gulf of Finland, east of Petergof, to Nicholas I.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] The new Alexandria Park, commissioned to Menelaws, became the last, and best preserved of the architect's projects.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] The work started with landscaping the territory and digging two large artificial pools; after Alexander's death, Nicholas commissioned Menelaws to build his summer residence, the asymmetrical *Cottage*.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Externally, it was more English than Gothic; Gothic influence was more obvious in the interiors designed by Menelaws.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] The park, laid down in English style, featured winding walkways around ponds, and had a Gothic Chapel (private church of the House of Romanov, designed by Karl Friedrich Schinkel) as its focal point (it was completed by Ludwig Charlemagne three years after Menelaws' death).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] It was suggested that Nicholas actually planned to relocate the remains of Alexander Nevsky into the chapel.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] The park also had facilities of the lesser rank: an animal sanctuary for old horses retired from the palace service, a farm and a menagerie with llama and elephant pavilions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Elephants lived in Alexandria until 1911 and were allowed to roam free in the summer.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/adam-menelaws] Menelaws died in Saint Petersburg during the cholera epidemic of 1831.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The **architecture of Scotland** includes all human building within the modern borders of Scotland, from the Neolithic era to the present day.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The earliest surviving houses go back around 9500 years, and the first villages 6000 years: Skara Brae on the Mainland of Orkney being the earliest preserved example in Europe.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Crannogs, roundhouses, each built on an artificial island, date from the Bronze Age and stone buildings called Atlantic roundhouses and larger earthwork hill forts from the Iron Age.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The arrival of the Romans from about 71 AD led to the creation of forts like that at Trimontium, and a continuous fortification between the Firth of Forth and the Firth of Clyde known as the Antonine Wall, built in the second century AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Beyond Roman influence, there is evidence of wheelhouses and underground souterrains.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] After the departure of the Romans there were a series of nucleated hill forts, often utilising major geographical features, as at Dunadd and Dunbarton.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Castles arrived in Scotland with the introduction of feudalism in the twelfth century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Initially these were wooden motte-and-bailey constructions, but many were replaced by stone castles with a high curtain wall.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In the late Middle Ages new castles were built, some on a grander scale, and others, particularly in the borders, simpler tower houses.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Gunpowder weaponry led to the use of gun ports, platforms to mount guns and walls adapted to resist bombardment.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Medieval parish church architecture was typically simpler than in England, but there were grander ecclesiastical buildings in the Gothic style.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] From the early fifteenth century the introduction of Renaissance styles included the selective use of Romanesque forms in church architecture, as in the nave of Dunkeld Cathedral, followed more directly influenced Renaissance palace building from the late fifteenth century, beginning at Linlithgow.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The private houses of aristocrats adopted some of these features and incorporated features of Medieval castles and tower houses into plans based on the French Château to produce the Scots Baronial style.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] From about 1560, the Reformation led to the widespread destruction of church furnishings, ornaments and decoration and in post-Reformation period a unique form of church emerged based on the T-shaped plan.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] After the Restoration in 1660, there was a fashion for grand private houses influenced by the Palladian style and associated with the architects Sir William Bruce and James Smith.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Scotland produced some of the most significant British architects of the eighteenth century, including: Colen Campbell, James Gibbs, William Chambers and particularly Robert Adam.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] They looked to classical models and Edinburgh's New Town was the focus of a classical building boom.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The Industrial Revolution transformed Scottish towns, leading to urban sprawl, exemplified by tenements like those of the Gorbals in Glasgow.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] New towns, of designed communities like New Lanark, developed from 1800 by Robert Owen, were one solution.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Sociologist Patrick Geddes (1854–1932) preferred "conservative surgery": retaining the best buildings in an area and removing the worst.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] There was a revival of the baronial style, particularly after the rebuilding of Abbotsford House for Walter Scott from 1816, and a parallel revival of the Gothic in church architecture.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Neoclassicism was pursued by William Henry Playfair, Alexander "Greek" Thomson and David Rhind.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The late nineteenth century saw some major engineering projects including the Forth Bridge, a cantilever bridge and one of the first major all steel constructions in the world.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The most significant Scottish architect of the early twentieth century, Charles Rennie Mackintosh, developed a unique and internationally influential "Glasgow style".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Architects who continued to employ styles informed by the past included James Robert Rhind and James Miller.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] From the mid-twentieth century, architecture in Scotland became increasingly utilitarian and influenced by modernism.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Key Scottish architects in this movement included Thomas S.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The introduction of brutalism led to urban clearances and extensive use of the tower block.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The style was also used in new towns like Glenrothes and Cumbernauld, but has received considerable criticism.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] More recent major architectural projects include the Scottish Exhibition and Conference Centre, Glasgow, the many striking modern buildings along the side of the River Clyde and the Scottish Parliament Building in Edinburgh.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Groups of settlers began building the first known permanent houses on what is now Scottish soil around 9500 years ago, and the first villages around 6000 years ago.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The stone building at Knap of Howar at Papa Westray, Orkney is one of the oldest surviving houses in north-west Europe, making use of locally gathered rubble in a dry-stone construction.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Skara Brae on the Mainland of Orkney also dates from this period and is Europe's most complete Neolithic village.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Neolithic habitation, burial and ritual sites are particularly common and well-preserved in the Northern Isles and Western Isles, where a lack of trees led to most structures being built of local stone.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] From the Early and Middle Bronze Age we have evidence of the occupation of crannogs, roundhouses partially or entirely built on an artificial island, usually in lakes, rivers and estuarine waters.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The peoples of early Iron Age Scotland, particularly in the north and west, lived in substantial stone buildings called Atlantic roundhouses.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The remains of hundreds of these houses exist throughout the country, some merely piles of rubble, others with impressive towers and outbuildings.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] They date from about 800 BC to AD 300 with the most imposing structures having been created circa 200–100 BC.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In the south and east larger earthwork hill forts survive.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] There is evidence for about 1,000 Iron Age hillforts in Scotland, most located below the Clyde-Forth line.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] They appear to have been largely abandoned in the Roman period, but some seem to have been reoccupied after their departure.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Most are circular, with a single palisade around an enclosure.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The Romans began military expeditions into what is now Scotland from about 71 AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In the summer of AD 78 Gnaeus Julius Agricola arrived in Britain to take up his appointment as the new governor and began a series of expeditions to Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Two years later his legions constructed a substantial fort at Trimontium near Melrose.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] He is said to have pushed his armies to the estuary of the "River Taus" (usually assumed to be the River Tay) and established forts there, including a legionary fortress at Inchtuthil.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Agricola's successors were unable or unwilling to further subdue the far north.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The fortress at Inchtuthil was dismantled before its completion and the other fortifications of the Gask Ridge were abandoned within the space of a few years.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] By AD 87 the occupation was limited to the Southern Uplands and by the end of the first century the northern limit of Roman expansion was a line drawn between the Tyne and Solway Firth.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Elginhaugh fort, in Midlothian, dates to about this period as may Castle Greg in West Lothian.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The Romans eventually withdrew to a line in what is now northern England, building the fortification known as Hadrian's Wall from coast to coast.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Around 141 A.D. the Romans undertook a reoccupation of southern Scotland, moving up to construct a new *limes* between the Firth of Forth and the Firth of Clyde.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The Antonine Wall is the largest Roman construction inside Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] It is a sward-covered wall made of turf circa 7 metres (20 ft) high, with nineteen forts.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Having taken twelve years to build, the wall was overrun and abandoned soon after AD 160.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The Romans retreated to the line of Hadrian's Wall, with occasional expeditions that involved the building and reoccupation of forts, until their departure in the fifth century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Beyond the area of Roman occupation, wheelhouses, a round house with a characteristic outer wall within which a circle of stone piers (bearing a resemblance to the spokes of a wheel) were constructed, with over sixty sites identified in the west and north.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Over 400 souterrains, small underground constructions, have been discovered in Scotland, many of them in the south-east, and although few have been dated those that have suggest a construction date in the 2nd or 3rd centuries AD.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] They are usually found close to settlements (whose timber frames are much less well-preserved) and may have been for storing perishable agricultural products.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] After the departure of the Romans we have evidence of a series of forts, often smaller "nucleated" constructions compared with Iron Age constructions, sometimes utilising major geographical features, as at Dunadd and Dumbarton.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Medieval vernacular architecture made use of local materials and styles.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] As in England, cruck construction was used, employing pairs of curved timbers to support the roof, however they were usually hidden from view.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In rural areas there was extensive use of turf to fill in the walls, sometimes on a stone base, but they were not long lasting and had to be rebuilt perhaps as often as every two or three years.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In some regions, including the south-west and around Dundee, solid clay walls were used, or combinations of clay, turf and stray, rendered with clay or lime to make them weatherproof.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] With a lack of long span structural timber, the most common building material was stone, employed in both mortared and dry stone construction.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Different regions used broom, heather, straw, turfs or reeds for roofing.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The introduction of Christianity into Scotland from Ireland, from the sixth century, led to the construction of basic masonry-built churches beginning on the west coast and islands.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Medieval parish church architecture in Scotland was typically much less elaborate than in England, with many churches remaining simple oblongs, without transepts and aisles, and often without towers.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In the Highlands they were often even simpler, many built of rubble masonry and sometimes indistinguishable from the outside from houses or farm buildings.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] However, from the eighth century, more sophisticated buildings emerged.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Early Romanesque ashlar masonry produced block-built stone buildings, like the eleventh century round tower at Brechin Cathedral and the square towers of Dunblane Cathedral and The Church of St Rule.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] After the eleventh century, as masonry techniques advanced, ashlar blocks became more rectangular, resulting in structurally more stable walls that could incorporate more refined architectural moulding and detailing that can be seen in corbelling, buttressing, lintels and arching.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In the fifteenth century continental builders are known to have been working in Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] French master-mason John Morrow was employed at the building of Glasgow Cathedral and the rebuilding of Melrose Abbey, both considered fine examples of Gothic architecture.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The interiors of churches were often elaborate before the Reformation, with highly decorated sacrament houses, like the ones surviving at Deskford and Kinkell.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The carvings at Rosslyn Chapel, created in the mid-fifteenth century, elaborately depicting the progression of the seven deadly sins, are considered some of the finest in the Gothic style.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Late Medieval Scottish churches also often contained elaborate burial monuments, like the Douglas tombs in the town of Douglas.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The early sixteenth century saw crown steeples built on churches with royal connections, symbolising imperial monarchy, as at St.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Scotland is known for its dramatically placed castles, many of which date from the late medieval era.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Castles, in the sense of a fortified residence of a lord or noble, arrived in Scotland as part of David I's encouragement of Norman and French nobles to settle with feudal tenures, particularly in the south and east, and were a way of controlling the contested lowlands.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] These were primarily wooden motte-and-bailey constructions, of a raised mount or motte, surmounted by a wooden tower and a larger adjacent enclosure or bailey, both usually surrounded by a fosse (a ditch) and palisade, and connected by a wooden bridge.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] They varied in size from the very large such as the Bass of Inverurie, to more modest designs like Balmaclellan.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In England many of these constructions were converted into stone "keep-and-bailey" castles in the twelfth century, but in Scotland most of those that were in continued occupation became stone castles of "enceinte", with a high embattled curtain wall.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The need for thick and high walls for defence forced the use of economic building methods, often continuing the tradition of dry-stone rubble building, which were then covered with a lime render, or harled for weatherproofing and a uniform appearance.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In addition to the baronial castles there were royal castles, often larger and providing defence, lodging for the itinerant Scottish court and a local administrative centre.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] By 1200 these included fortifications at Ayr and Berwick.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In the wars of Scottish Independence Robert I adopted a policy of castle destruction, rather than allow fortresses to be easily retaken and then held by the English, beginning with his own castles at Ayr and Dumfries, and including Roxburgh and Edinburgh.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] After the Wars of Independence, new castles began to be built, often on a grander scale as "livery and maintenance" castles, to house retained troops, like Tantallon, Lothian and Doune near Stirling, rebuilt for Robert Stewart, Duke of Albany in the fourteenth century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The largest number of late medieval fortifications in Scotland built by nobles, about 800, were of the tower house design.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Smaller versions of tower houses in southern Scotland were known as peel towers, or pele houses.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The defences of tower houses were primarily aimed to provide protection against smaller raiding parties and were not intended to put up significant opposition to an organised military assault, leading historian Stuart Reid to characterise them as "defensible rather than defensive".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] They were typically a tall, square, stone-built, crenelated building; often also surrounded by a barmkin or bawn, a walled courtyard designed to hold valuable animals securely, but not necessarily intended for serious defence.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] They were built extensively on both sides of the border with England and James IV's forfeiture of the Lordship of the Isles in 1494 led to an immediate burst of castle building across the region.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Gunpowder weaponry fundamentally altered the nature of castle architecture, with existing castles being adapted to allow the use of gunpowder weapons by the incorporation of "keyhole" gun ports, platforms to mount guns and walls being adapted to resist bombardment.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Ravenscraig, Kirkcaldy, begun about 1460, is probably the first castle in the British Isles to be built as an Artillery fort, incorporating "D-shape" bastions that would better resist cannon fire and on which artillery could be mounted.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The impact of the Renaissance on Scottish architecture has been seen as occurring in two distinct phases.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] First, from the early fifteenth century the selective use of Romanesque forms in church architecture, to be followed by a second phase of more directly influenced Renaissance palace building from the late fifteenth century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] It can be seen in the nave of Dunkeld Cathedral, begun in 1406, the facade of St Mary's, Haddington from the 1460s and in the chapel of Bishop Elphinstone's Kings College, Aberdeen (1500–9).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] About forty collegiate churches were established in Scotland in late fifteenth and early sixteenth centuries.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Many, like Trinity College, Edinburgh, showed a combination of Gothic and Renaissance styles.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The extensive building and rebuilding of royal palaces probably began under James III, accelerated under James IV, reaching its peak under James V.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] These works have been seen as directly reflecting the influence of Renaissance styles.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Linlithgow was first constructed under James I, under the direction of master of work John de Waltoun and was referred to as a palace, apparently the first use of this term in the country, from 1429.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] This was extended under James III and began to correspond to a fashionable quadrangular, corner-towered Italian signorial palace of a *palatium ad moden castri* (a castle-style palace), combining classical symmetry with neo-chivalric imagery.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] There is evidence of Italian masons working for James IV, in whose reign Linlithgow was completed and other palaces were rebuilt with Italianate proportions.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] James V encountered the French version of Renaissance building while visiting for his marriage to Madeleine of Valois in 1536 and his second marriage to Mary of Guise may have resulted in longer term connections and influences.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Work from his reign largely disregarded the insular style adopted in England under Henry VIII and adopted forms that were recognisably European, beginning with the extensive work at Linlithgow.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] This was followed by re-buildings at Holyrood, Falkland, Stirling and Edinburgh, described as "some of the finest examples of Renaissance architecture in Britain".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Rather than slavishly copying continental forms, most Scottish architecture incorporated elements of these styles into traditional local patterns, adapting them to Scottish idioms and materials (particularly stone and harl).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Work undertaken for James VI demonstrated continued Renaissance influences, with the Chapel Royal at Stirling having a classical entrance built in 1594 and the North Wing of Linlithgow, built in 1618, using classical pediments.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Similar themes can be seen in the private houses of aristocrats, as in Mar's Wark, Stirling (c.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] 1570) and Crichton Castle, built for the Earl of Bothwell in 1580s.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] From about 1560, the Reformation revolutionised church architecture in Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Calvinists rejected ornamentation in places of worship, with no need for elaborate buildings divided up by ritual, resulting in the widespread destruction of Medieval church furnishings, ornaments and decoration.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] There was a need to adapt and build new churches suitable for reformed services, particularly putting the pulpit and preaching at the centre of worship.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] There were continuities with pre-Reformation materials, with some churches using rubble, as at Kemback in Fife (1582).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Others employed stone and a few added wooden steeples, as at Burntisland (1592).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The church of Greyfriars, Edinburgh, built between 1602 and 1620, used a rectangular layout with a largely Gothic form, but that at Dirleton (1612), had a more sophisticated classical style.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] A variation of the rectangular church that developed in post-Reformation Scotland was the T-shaped plan, often used when adapting existing churches, which allowed the maximum number of parishioners to be near the pulpit.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] They can be seen at Kemback and Prestonpans after 1595.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] It continued to be used into the seventeenth century as at Weem (1600), Anstruther Easter, Fife (1634–44) and New Cumnock (1657).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In the seventeenth century a Greek cross plan was used for churches such as Cawdor (1619) and Fenwick (1643).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In most of these cases one arm of the cross would have been closed off as a laird's aisle, meaning that they were in effect T-plan churches.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The unique style of great private house in Scotland, later known as Scots baronial, has been located in origin to the period of the 1560s.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] It kept many of the features of the high walled Medieval castles that had been largely made obsolete by gunpowder weapons and may have been influenced by the French masons brought to Scotland to work on royal palaces.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] It drew on the tower houses and peel towers, retaining many of their external features, but with a larger ground plan, classically a stone built "Z-plan" of a rectangular block with towers, as at Colliston Castle (1583) and Claypotts Castle (1569–88).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Particularly influential was the work of William Wallace, the king's master mason from 1617 until his death in 1631.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] He worked on the rebuilding of the collapsed North Range of Linlithgow from 1618, Winton House for George Seton, 3rd Earl of Winton and began work on Heriot's Hospital, Edinburgh.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] He adopted a distinctive style that applied elements of Scottish fortification and Flemish influences to a Renaissance plan like that used at Château d'Ancy-le-Franc.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] This style can be seen in lords houses built at Caerlaverlock (1620), Moray House, Edinburgh (1628) and Drumlanrig Castle (1675–89), and was highly influential until the baronial style gave way to the grander English forms associated with Inigo Jones in the later seventeenth century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] During the turbulent era of Civil Wars and the English occupation of Scotland, significant building in Scotland was largely confined to military architecture, with polygonal fortresses with triangular bastions at Ayr, Inverness and Leith in the style of the trace italienne.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] After the Restoration in 1660, large scale building began again, often incorporating more comprehensive ideas of reviving classicism.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Sir William Bruce (1630–1710), considered "the effective founder of classical architecture in Scotland", was the key figure in introducing the Palladian style into Scotland, following the principles of the Venetian architect Andrea Palladio (1508–80).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Palladio's ideas were strongly based on the symmetry, perspective and values of the formal classical temple architecture of the Ancient Greeks and Romans, and associated in England with the designs of Inigo Jones.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Bruce popularised a style of country house amongst the nobility that encouraging the move towards a more continental, leisure-oriented architecture.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] He built and remodelled country houses, including Thirlestane Castle and Prestonfield House.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Among his most significant work was his own Palladian mansion at Kinross, built on the Loch Leven estate which he had purchased in 1675.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] As the Surveyor and Overseer of the Royal Works he undertook the rebuilding of the Royal Palace of Holyroodhouse in the 1670s, which gave the palace its present appearance.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] After the death of Charles II, Bruce lost political favour, and later, following the Glorious Revolution, he was imprisoned more than once as a suspected Jacobite.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] These houses were predominantly built using well-cut ashlar masonry on the façades, while rubble stonework was used only for internal walls.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] James Smith worked as a mason on the Bruce's rebuilding of Holyrood Palace.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In 1683 he was appointed to be Surveyor and Overseer of the Royal Works, and was responsible for maintenance of Holyrood Palace, and refurbished the former Holyrood Abbey as a chapel royal for King James VII.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] With his father-in-law, the master mason Robert Mylne, Smith worked on Caroline Park in Edinburgh (1685), and Drumlanrig Castle (1680s).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Smith's country houses followed the pattern established by William Bruce, with hipped roofs and pedimented fronts, in a plain but handsome Palladian style.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] His Canongate Kirk (1688–90) is a basilica-plan, with a baroque facade.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In 1691 Smith designed the mausoleum of Sir George Mackenzie of Rosehaugh, in Greyfriars Kirkyard, a circular structure modelled on the Tempietto di San Pietro, designed by Donato Bramante (1444–1514).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Hamilton Palace (1695) was fronted by giant Corinthian columns, and a pedimented entrance, although was otherwise restrained.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Dalkeith Palace (1702–10) was modelled after William of Orange's palace at Het Loo in the Netherlands.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] After the Act of Union, growing prosperity in Scotland led to a spate of new building, both public and private.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The threat of Jacobite insurrection or invasion meant that Scotland also saw more military building than England in this period, relying on the strength of inclined and angled engineered masonry work combined with the ability of earthen toppings that could deflect and absorb artillery fire.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] This culminated in the construction of Fort George, near Inverness (1748–69), with its projecting bastions and redoubts.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Scotland produced some of the most significant architects of this era, including: Colen Campbell (1676–1729), James Gibbs (1682–1754), James (1732–94), John (1721–92) and Robert Adam (1728–92) and William Chambers (1723–96), who all created work that to some degree looked to classical models.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Edinburgh's New Town was the focus of this classical building boom in Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] From the mid-eighteenth century it was laid out according to a plan of rectangular blocks with open squares, drawn up by James Craig and built in strong Craigleith sandstone which could be precisely cut by masons.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Most residences were built as tenement flats, where, in contrast to contemporary building in England where buildings were divided vertically into different houses, they were divided horizontally, with different occupants sharing a common staircase.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The smallest might have only one room, the largest several bedrooms and drawing rooms.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] This classicism, together with its reputation as a major centre of the Enlightenment, resulted in the city being nicknamed "The Athens of the North".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The gridiron plan, building forms and the architectural detailing would be copied by many smaller towns, although rendered in locally quarried materials.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Despite this building boom, the centralisation of much of the government administration, including the king's works, in London, meant that a number of Scottish architects spent most of all of their careers in England, where they had a major impact on Georgian architecture.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Colen Campbell was influenced by the Palladian style and has been credited with founding Georgian architecture.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Architectural historian Howard Colvin has speculated that he was associated with James Smith and that Campbell may even have been his pupil.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] He spent most of his career in Italy and England and developed a rivalry with fellow Scot James Gibbs.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Gibbs trained in Rome and also practised mainly in England.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] His architectural style did incorporate Palladian elements, as well as forms from Italian baroque and Inigo Jones, but was most strongly influenced by the interpretation of the Baroque by Sir Christopher Wren.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] William Adam, was the foremost architect of his time in Scotland, designing and building numerous country houses and public buildings.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Among his best known works are Hopetoun House near Edinburgh, and Duff House in Banff.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] His individual, exuberant, style was built on the Palladian style, but with Baroque details inspired by Vanbrugh and Continental architecture.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] After his death, his sons Robert and John took on the family business, which included lucrative work for the Board of Ordnance.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Robert emerged as leader of the first phase of the neo-classical revival in England and Scotland from around 1760 until his death.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] He rejected the Palladian style as "ponderous" and "disgustful".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] However, he continued their tradition of drawing inspiration directly from classical antiquity, influenced by his four-year stay in Europe.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] An interior designer as well as an architect, with his brothers developing the Adam style, he influenced the development of architecture, not just in Britain, but in Western Europe, North America and in Russia, where his patterns were taken by Scottish architect Charles Cameron.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Adam's main rival was William Chambers, another Scot, but born in Sweden.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] He did most of his work in London, with a small number of houses in Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] He was appointed architectural tutor to the Prince of Wales, later George III, and in 1766, with Robert Adam, as Architect to the King.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] More international in outlook than Adam, he combined Neoclassicism and Palladian conventions and his influence was mediated through his large number of pupils.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Vernacular architecture of this period continued to depend on local materials and styles, increasing making use of locally mined stone.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] While Edinburgh made extensive use of yellow sandstone, the commercial centre and tenements of Glasgow were built in distinctive red sandstone.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Often built by groups of friends and family, the homes of the poor were usually of very simple construction.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Contemporaries noted that cottages in the Highlands and Islands tended to be cruder, with single rooms, slit windows and earthen floors, often shared by a large family.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In contrast many Lowland cottages had distinct rooms and chambers, were clad with plaster or paint and even had glazed windows.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Urban settings also included traditional thatched houses, beside the larger, stone and slate roofed town houses of merchants and urban gentry.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The Industrial Revolution transformed the scale of Scottish towns, making Glasgow the "second city of the Empire".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The sometimes utopian concept of the new town, aimed at improving society through the foundation of architecturally designed communities, was an important part of Scottish thinking from the mid-eighteenth to the twentieth century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In addition to the New Town of Edinburgh these included the complete rebuilding of Inverary for John Campbell, 5th Duke of Argyll by John Adam and Robert Mylne, between 1772 and 1800.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] From 1800, Robert Owen's New Lanark, designed as a self-contained community, combining industry with ordered and improved living conditions, was an important milestone in the historical development of urban planning.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] He put this into practice, purchasing and improving slum tenements in James Court, and in new developments at Ramsay Garden, Edinburgh.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The Gothic Revival in architecture has been seen as an expression of Romanticism and according to Alvin Jackson, the Scots baronial style was "a Caledonian reading of the gothic".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Some of the earliest evidence of a revival in Gothic architecture is from Scotland.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Inveraray Castle, constructed from 1746 with design input from William Adam displays the incorporation of turrets.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] These were largely conventional Palladian style houses that incorporated some external features of the Scots baronial style.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Robert Adam's houses in this style include Mellerstain and Wedderburn in Berwickshire and Seton House in East Lothian, but it is most clearly seen at Culzean Castle, Ayrshire, remodelled by Adam from 1777.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Important for the adoption of the style in the early nineteenth century was Abbotsford House, the residence the novelist and poet, Sir Walter Scott.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Re-built for him from 1816, it became a model for the modern revival of the baronial style.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Common features borrowed from sixteenth- and seventeenth-century houses included battlemented gateways, crow-stepped gables, pointed turrets and machicolations.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The style was popular across Scotland and was applied to many relatively modest dwellings by architects such as William Burn (1789–1870), David Bryce (1803–76), Edward Blore (1787–1879), Edward Calvert (c.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] 1847–1914) and Robert Stodart Lorimer (1864–1929) and in urban contexts, including the building of Cockburn Street in Edinburgh (from the 1850s) as well as the National Wallace Monument at Stirling (1859–69).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The rebuilding of Balmoral Castle as a baronial palace and its adoption as a royal retreat from 1855 to 1858 confirmed the popularity of the style.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In ecclesiastical architecture, a style with more in common to that in England was adopted.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Important figures included Frederick Thomas Pilkington (1832–98), who developed a new style of church building which accorded with the fashionable High Gothic, but which adapted it for the worship needs of the Free Church of Scotland, as at Barclay Viewforth Church, Edinburgh (1862–64).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Robert Rowand Anderson (1834–1921), who trained in the office of George Gilbert Scott in London before returning to Edinburgh, worked mainly on small churches in the 'First Pointed' (or Early English) style that is characteristic of Scott's former assistants.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Neoclassicism continued to be a major style into the nineteenth century.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] William Henry Playfair (1790–1857) was the designer of many of Edinburgh's neoclassical landmarks in the New Town.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Two of his finest works are the National Gallery of Scotland and the Royal Scottish Academy, which are situated in the centre of Edinburgh.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] However, the figure most associated with the classical style was Alexander "Greek" Thomson (1817–75).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Working mainly in Glasgow, he turned away from the Gothic style toward that of the ancient Greeks and Egyptians, as can be seen in the temple and columns that were part of the Caledonia Road Church (1856).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] David Rhind (1808–83) employed both neoclassical and Baronial styles and his work included many branches of the Commercial Bank of Scotland, including their headquarters in Edinburgh.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] He also designed a number of churches, local government buildings, and houses.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] One of his grandest schemes was Daniel Stewart's Hospital, now Stewart's Melville College, Edinburgh.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In 1849, he was commissioned to design the lay-out of the Pollokshields area of Glasgow, in what until then had been farmland 2 miles (3.2 km) south of the city centre.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The partnership was to execute important projects such as the Queen Victoria Memorial at Liverpool and the Royal Scots War Memorial in St Giles' Cathedral, Edinburgh.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The nineteenth century saw some major engineering projects including Thomas Telford's stone Dean Bridge and iron Craigellachie Bridge.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The most important was the Forth Bridge, a cantilever railway bridge over the Firth of Forth in the east of Scotland, 14 kilometres (9 mi) west of central Edinburgh.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Construction of a suspension bridge designed by Thomas Bouch, was stopped after the collapse of another of his works, the Tay Bridge.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The project was taken over by John Fowler and Benjamin Baker, who designed a structure that was built by Glasgow-based company Sir William Arrol & Co. from 1883.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] It was opened on 4 March 1890, and spans a total length of 2,528.7 metres (8,296 ft).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] It was the first major structure in Britain to be constructed of steel; its contemporary, the Eiffel Tower was built of wrought iron.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The most significant Scottish architect of the early twentieth century, having a considerable influence on European architecture, was Charles Rennie Mackintosh (1868–1928).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] He mixed elements of the Scots baronial, Arts and Crafts Movement and the Art Nouveau to produce elegant modern buildings.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] His major work included The Willow Tearooms in Sauchiehall Street, Glasgow (1903), Glasgow School of Art (1897–1909) and Hill House, Helensburgh (1902–04).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In the 20th century the distinctive Scottish use of stone architecture declined as it was replaced by cheaper alternatives such as Portland cement, concrete, and mass-production brick.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Stone would however be retained as a material for some housing stock in Edinburgh, Aberdeen and Dumfries, and would undergo revivals.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In the twentieth century private architecture was increasingly client driven.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] James Robert Rhind (1854–1918), the son of David Rhind, was successful in the competition for new libraries to be constructed in Glasgow following Andrew Carnegie's gift of £100,000 to the city in 1901.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] His designs were selected for seven libraries, allowing him to demonstrate his individual interpretation of Edwardian Baroque architecture.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Rhind's libraries were all built with locally quarried sandstone, which blended in with the existing tenement neighbourhoods.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] His landmark buildings were greatly enhanced by his liberal use of columns, domes and sculpted features.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] James Miller (1860–1947) is noted for his Scottish railway stations, such as his 1901–05 extensions to Glasgow Central railway station, and the spectacular Wemyss Bay railway station on the Firth of Clyde.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] After the First World War, Miller and his chief designer Richard Gunn (1889–1933) along with others, adapted to the growing needs of the office block.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In Glasgow, with its central gridiron plan, this followed the practice in the United States of filling up entire blocks and building steel framed buildings as high as the fire marshal would allow, as in the heavily American-influenced Union Bank building (1924) at St Vincent Street.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] From the mid-twentieth century, public architecture became more utilitarian, as part of the impulse to produce a comprehensive welfare state.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] During World War I the government became increasingly aware of Scotland's housing problems, particularly after the Glasgow rent strike of 1915.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The result was a massive programme of council house building.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Many early council houses were built on greenfield sites away from the pollution of the city, often constructed of semi-detached homes or terraced cottages.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Knightswood, north-west of Glasgow, was built as a show piece from 1923 to 1929, with a library, social centre and seven shopping "parades".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] In the 1930s schemes tended to be more cheaply built, like Blackhill, Glasgow, with a thousand houses built as two and three-story tenements.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] These building schemes were designed to rehouse those displaced by urban slum clearance, by which thousands of tenements were demolished.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] However, often crammed into poor land near railways or gasworks, they soon became notorious.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] A survey of 1936 found that almost half of Scotland's houses were still inadequate.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Their later work, almost all of it outside Scotland, would be highly influential on an international scale.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The post-war desire for urban regeneration would focus on the tower block, championed in Glasgow by David Gibson, convener of the city housing committee.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Projects like the brutalist Red Road Flats originally offered hope of a new beginning and an escape from the overcrowded nineteenth-century tenements of the city, but lacked a sufficient infrastructure and soon deteriorated.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Robert Matthew (1906–75) and Basil Spence (1907–76) were responsible for redeveloping the Gorbals in Glasgow, for demolitions at the University of Edinburgh and the stark rebuilding typified by the David Hume Tower (1960–63, now named 40 George Square).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Another solution adopted in Scotland was the building of new towns like Glenrothes (1948) and Cumbernauld (1956), designed to take excess population from the cities.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Cumbernauld was praised for its architecture when first built, but the uncompleted centre and the layout of the town in general, were receiving heavy criticism by the twenty-first century: its modernist architecture described by one resident as "the lego fantasy of an unhappy child".
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] From the 1980s Scottish architecture began to recover its reputation with works such as the building to house the Burrell Collection in Glasgow (1981).
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] The most important building of the early twenty-first century is the Scottish Parliament Building in Edinburgh, designed by Enric Miralles (1955–2000) and opened in 2004, with a design that recalls upturned fishing boats.
[src:architecture-of-scotland/architecture-of-scotland-p01] Urban regeneration has also been attempted in areas of post-industrial decline, like the Merchant City in Glasgow, which was returned to housing from the 1980s, with warehouse loft conversions and more recently the waterfront in Edinburgh, resulting in a return of populations to major urban centres.
